ANJALI KUMAR: Wow.

00:38:05.860 --> 00:38:07.330
I really want to come back.

00:38:07.330 --> 00:38:08.290
Don't ever leave.

00:38:08.290 --> 00:38:10.060
That is the secret.

00:38:10.060 --> 00:38:13.720
Joking aside, I think it's
being really intentional

00:38:13.720 --> 00:38:16.640
about carving out the time
and doing it no matter what.

00:38:16.640 --> 00:38:19.570
And I think if you start--
when I did that first TM class,

00:38:19.570 --> 00:38:22.055
I remember they said you
had to do it for two months,

00:38:22.055 --> 00:38:23.680
I think, where they're
like, try to not

00:38:23.680 --> 00:38:25.630
break the habit or the
streak for two months,

00:38:25.630 --> 00:38:27.730
and then it just
became a thing I did.

00:38:27.730 --> 00:38:29.590
Where now, I'm not
a morning person,

00:38:29.590 --> 00:38:31.600
and I will wake
up early to do it.

00:38:31.600 --> 00:38:35.185
So if you can, I would start
by just waking up early,

00:38:35.185 --> 00:38:37.060
like if it's 20 minutes,
10 minutes, whatever

00:38:37.060 --> 00:38:38.440
your practice is.

00:38:38.440 --> 00:38:41.200
And then if you're trying to
find space during the day,

00:38:41.200 --> 00:38:44.362
if you can block off a
meeting, I would do that.

00:38:44.362 --> 00:38:45.820
And I think in a
place like Google,

00:38:45.820 --> 00:38:47.140
people respect it actually.

00:38:47.140 --> 00:38:49.280
It's not necessarily
true of other workplaces.

00:38:49.280 --> 00:38:50.410
I can tell you that,
because they'll be like,

00:38:50.410 --> 00:38:51.570
we've got a meeting.

00:38:51.570 --> 00:38:53.530
This is the only other
time everyone can meet

00:38:53.530 --> 00:38:54.730
and they just schedule over it.

00:38:54.730 --> 00:38:56.980
But I feel like here, you could
actually carve that space.

00:38:56.980 --> 00:38:59.382
CRISTIN FRODELLA: Have you
done "Search Inside Yourself?

00:38:59.382 --> 00:39:00.507
AUDIENCE: No.

00:39:00.507 --> 00:39:02.590
CRISTIN FRODELLA: So there
is a course here called

00:39:02.590 --> 00:39:05.048
"Search Inside Yourself," which
is essentially a meditation

00:39:05.048 --> 00:39:11.910
course started by an ex-Googler
who's an incredible guy, Meng.

00:39:11.910 --> 00:39:14.230
Anyway, so "Search Inside
Yourself" is a course here.

00:39:14.230 --> 00:39:19.720
And at the end of it, you get
paired up with a fellow SIY

00:39:19.720 --> 00:39:24.340
alumni, and the goal is
essentially you have meetings

00:39:24.340 --> 00:39:26.920
together so that you can carve
out the time to meditate.

00:39:26.920 --> 00:39:30.940
And if you write to that list,
which is SIY dash alumni--

00:39:30.940 --> 00:39:33.270
I don't know actually if
you'll be able to access it,

00:39:33.270 --> 00:39:36.100
but there are tons
of people who I'm

00:39:36.100 --> 00:39:38.470
sure would love to
set up time with you.

00:39:38.470 --> 00:39:39.384
AUDIENCE: Great.

00:39:39.384 --> 00:39:42.583
Thank you.

00:39:42.583 --> 00:39:43.500
Hi.

00:39:43.500 --> 00:39:45.390
So I feel like
maybe the questions

00:39:45.390 --> 00:39:47.764
that you started with in this
book and the questions that

00:39:47.764 --> 00:39:50.430
kind of started this talk
are generally like universal

00:39:50.430 --> 00:39:52.950
among people, and I think
that everyone kind of wonders

00:39:52.950 --> 00:39:54.967
about a lot of these things.

00:39:54.967 --> 00:39:56.550
Thinking about like
myself personally,

00:39:56.550 --> 00:40:01.020
I think my instincts, or like
whatever my first movement here

00:40:01.020 --> 00:40:03.322
would be to think
about exploring

00:40:03.322 --> 00:40:05.780
the more major religions and
the more mainstream religions.

00:40:05.780 --> 00:40:07.780
And I think that a lot
of the stuff you explored

00:40:07.780 --> 00:40:09.570
would kind of be a
secondary thought.

00:40:09.570 --> 00:40:11.910
Can you talk a little bit
more about your decision

00:40:11.910 --> 00:40:14.956
to kind of go that route instead
of the more mainstream religion

00:40:14.956 --> 00:40:15.455
route?

00:40:15.455 --> 00:40:16.246
ANJALI KUMAR: Yeah.

00:40:16.246 --> 00:40:19.470
It was really because
I'm not a theologian

00:40:19.470 --> 00:40:21.340
and I didn't feel
drawn to any of them,

00:40:21.340 --> 00:40:25.674
so I didn't feel like I
could do an adequate job

00:40:25.674 --> 00:40:27.840
of like exploring Christianity
and then a little bit

00:40:27.840 --> 00:40:28.990
of Judaism and then Islam.

00:40:28.990 --> 00:40:31.290
It's like, how do you do
that in a meaningful way

00:40:31.290 --> 00:40:33.420
with a full-time
job with a new kid?

00:40:33.420 --> 00:40:35.520
And I didn't feel
drawn to any of them,

00:40:35.520 --> 00:40:37.650
because I don't think this
project was necessarily

00:40:37.650 --> 00:40:40.170
a rejection of the
religion I was raised with.

00:40:40.170 --> 00:40:42.329
If you asked me now,
what religion are you?

00:40:42.329 --> 00:40:43.620
I'd probably still answer Jain.

00:40:43.620 --> 00:40:44.500
I'm Jainish.

00:40:44.500 --> 00:40:46.470
Like people are
Jewish, I'm Jainish.

00:40:46.470 --> 00:40:48.360
You know, that's
still directionally

00:40:48.360 --> 00:40:51.870
what I feel makes sense for me
because it's so cultural to me.

00:40:51.870 --> 00:40:56.670
So I think because I tied
religion and culture so much

00:40:56.670 --> 00:41:00.510
together, it would be like
searching for a new culture,

00:41:00.510 --> 00:41:02.580
and that wasn't
really the project.

00:41:02.580 --> 00:41:04.580
But a lot of people have
asked me that question.

00:41:04.580 --> 00:41:07.440
Yeah, it wasn't something that
felt like the right direction.

00:41:07.440 --> 00:41:11.784
And so I went in this
kind of other direction.

00:41:11.784 --> 00:41:13.200
But everything
that I searched for

00:41:13.200 --> 00:41:14.910
and all the
experiences that I did

00:41:14.910 --> 00:41:17.954
were very much authentically
what I felt curious about.

00:41:17.954 --> 00:41:20.370
And so it wasn't like, oh,
what will make a funny chapter.

00:41:20.370 --> 00:41:20.850
It was like, no.

00:41:20.850 --> 00:41:22.440
I kind of want to
go to Burning Man

00:41:22.440 --> 00:41:24.315
and I think I want to
do a silent meditation.

00:41:24.315 --> 00:41:27.321
Like it was things that
I actually wanted to try.

00:41:27.321 --> 00:41:29.030
AUDIENCE: Can I ask
a follow-up question?

00:41:29.030 --> 00:41:30.764
ANJALI KUMAR: Please, yeah.

00:41:30.764 --> 00:41:32.430
AUDIENCE: Can you
talk a little bit more

00:41:32.430 --> 00:41:34.290
about the title of
the book, because I

00:41:34.290 --> 00:41:36.190
feel like this may be--

00:41:36.190 --> 00:41:38.580
like, God is something
that I associate maybe more

00:41:38.580 --> 00:41:43.265
with mainstream religions than
with other spiritual practices,

00:41:43.265 --> 00:41:45.390
and I'd be interested to
hear kind of your thoughts

00:41:45.390 --> 00:41:47.310
about the connection
between those and God.

00:41:47.310 --> 00:41:48.510
ANJALI KUMAR: Sure.

00:41:48.510 --> 00:41:50.370
So the original
title of the book

00:41:50.370 --> 00:41:54.205
that I sold the proposal on was
actually "From Google to God."

00:41:54.205 --> 00:41:56.580
And I loved it and I thought
it was really a funny title,

00:41:56.580 --> 00:41:59.084
and then my editor, halfway
through my writing process,

00:41:59.084 --> 00:42:00.750
was like, you've got
to change the title

00:42:00.750 --> 00:42:03.180
because it sounds like you
left Google to become a priest.

00:42:03.180 --> 00:42:04.140
And I was like, aw.

00:42:04.140 --> 00:42:06.720
That's true and that's not
what happens in this book.

00:42:06.720 --> 00:42:10.830
But the idea of it
just being a search,

00:42:10.830 --> 00:42:13.020
I wanted some reference
to the tech kind

00:42:13.020 --> 00:42:16.470
of piece of it and the fact that
tech played such a large part

00:42:16.470 --> 00:42:20.980
certainly in my personal journey
in just of life and my career,

00:42:20.980 --> 00:42:24.210
but then also in how I was
accessing a lot of these things

00:42:24.210 --> 00:42:26.750
because so much of it started
with an internet search.

00:42:26.750 --> 00:42:29.760
You know, that was
part of the narrative.

00:42:29.760 --> 00:42:31.350
The stalking
reference, you know,

00:42:31.350 --> 00:42:34.389
it's a bit of a provocative
sort of word to use.

00:42:34.389 --> 00:42:36.180
But it's certainly like
a Facebook stalking

00:42:36.180 --> 00:42:38.730
kind of reference of like--
but again, tongue in cheek.

00:42:38.730 --> 00:42:41.790
So there was a lot of
thought put into the title,

00:42:41.790 --> 00:42:44.370
and I think it can be
confusing to people.

00:42:44.370 --> 00:42:46.110
There's definitely
Amazon reviewers

00:42:46.110 --> 00:42:47.970
who do not like my
book because they're

00:42:47.970 --> 00:42:51.311
like, that's not the answer
and Christianity is the answer,

00:42:51.311 --> 00:42:51.810
whatever.

00:42:51.810 --> 00:42:54.960
There's a couple of very
angry people on Amazon.

00:42:54.960 --> 00:42:58.650
And I was like, well, then
it's not for you and I get it.

00:42:58.650 --> 00:43:01.957
But it was meant to be a
bit tongue in cheek too.

00:43:01.957 --> 00:43:02.790
AUDIENCE: Thank you.

00:43:02.790 --> 00:43:03.665
ANJALI KUMAR: Thanks.

00:43:05.946 --> 00:43:08.980
AUDIENCE: My first question
was the same as his actually.

00:43:08.980 --> 00:43:12.820
My next question is, was
anybody actually healed,

00:43:12.820 --> 00:43:15.597
like that you took to
the Brazilian healer guy,

00:43:15.597 --> 00:43:17.055
like the people's
photos and stuff?

00:43:17.055 --> 00:43:17.860
ANJALI KUMAR: Oh, the follow-up.

00:43:17.860 --> 00:43:19.760
AUDIENCE: Like did
anybody ever actually--

00:43:19.760 --> 00:43:21.460
ANJALI KUMAR: Of the photos--

00:43:21.460 --> 00:43:23.200
so I don't think
anyone I brought

00:43:23.200 --> 00:43:26.510
photos of was struggling
with a real medical condition

00:43:26.510 --> 00:43:30.310
of the batch that I had.

00:43:30.310 --> 00:43:33.400
But that said, in follow-ups--

00:43:33.400 --> 00:43:36.220
so John of God also makes a
trip to like Omega Institute

00:43:36.220 --> 00:43:37.700
in upstate New York.

00:43:37.700 --> 00:43:42.355
And so I had gone last year
before my book came out.

00:43:42.355 --> 00:43:44.980
I drove up there because he was
coming, and I was kind of like,

00:43:44.980 --> 00:43:48.310
I feel like I should show a
picture of my book cover to him

00:43:48.310 --> 00:43:49.800
and have him scan
that and heal it.

00:43:49.800 --> 00:43:52.692
I thought it'd be kind of like
a nice tying up for myself.

00:43:52.692 --> 00:43:55.150
I don't know if he did it, but
I left a picture of the book

00:43:55.150 --> 00:43:58.510
cover in his basket,
and I did bring

00:43:58.510 --> 00:44:01.540
a photograph of a friend who
was just diagnosed with breast

00:44:01.540 --> 00:44:06.097
cancer, and she is cancer free.

00:44:06.097 --> 00:44:07.180
I don't think that did it.

00:44:07.180 --> 00:44:09.880
I mean, she also had
medical treatment.

00:44:09.880 --> 00:44:11.620
But I don't know.

00:44:11.620 --> 00:44:15.240
If it gives somebody a little
bit of hope, I think that's OK.

00:44:15.240 --> 00:44:15.920
AUDIENCE: Cool.

00:44:15.920 --> 00:44:16.420
Thank you.

00:44:16.420 --> 00:44:18.040
ANJALI KUMAR: Yeah.

00:44:18.040 --> 00:44:19.450
AUDIENCE: Hi, Anjali.

00:44:19.450 --> 00:44:21.720
Thank you for coming.

00:44:21.720 --> 00:44:25.140
I really enjoyed that,
especially because last night,

00:44:25.140 --> 00:44:28.360
I had like my monthly
existential crisis

00:44:28.360 --> 00:44:31.880
reflecting on like
these sorts of ideas.

00:44:31.880 --> 00:44:33.835
And one of the thoughts
that came was--

00:44:33.835 --> 00:44:36.460
and this is actually a follow-up
from a podcast I was listening

00:44:36.460 --> 00:44:37.640
to earlier this week--

00:44:37.640 --> 00:44:40.600
was that this sort of
rationalist mindset, the very

00:44:40.600 --> 00:44:44.620
scientific driven
mindset is fairly modern.

00:44:44.620 --> 00:44:47.740
Like it's a byproduct of the
post-industrial revolution

00:44:47.740 --> 00:44:48.910
movements.

00:44:48.910 --> 00:44:53.710
And it's sort of like when
you have that mindset where

00:44:53.710 --> 00:44:57.070
you want to critically analyze,
OK, why is this happening,

00:44:57.070 --> 00:45:00.040
I found that, even
doing meditation,

00:45:00.040 --> 00:45:01.620
my first thought
after is like, OK.

00:45:01.620 --> 00:45:03.640
I felt something, but
like why did I feel that?

00:45:03.640 --> 00:45:06.100
It has to be some like
neurological process

00:45:06.100 --> 00:45:06.940
that's causing this.

00:45:06.940 --> 00:45:09.436
Clearly, there has to be a
rational explanation for that.

00:45:09.436 --> 00:45:10.810
So when you're
doing all of these

00:45:10.810 --> 00:45:14.140
like very unorthodox
things, did you

00:45:14.140 --> 00:45:18.010
find that you needed to suspend
that sort of mindset of like,

00:45:18.010 --> 00:45:18.910
OK.

00:45:18.910 --> 00:45:20.590
There has to be a
clearly rational way

00:45:20.590 --> 00:45:22.060
to explain why
this is happening.

00:45:22.060 --> 00:45:23.150
ANJALI KUMAR: Yeah, 100%.

00:45:23.150 --> 00:45:27.760
So when you read my
book, the narrative

00:45:27.760 --> 00:45:29.330
really plays out that way.

00:45:29.330 --> 00:45:32.080
There's like this a
very lawyerly part

00:45:32.080 --> 00:45:36.100
of me that does the research
and will talk about oxytocin

00:45:36.100 --> 00:45:38.522
release during a hug and
like what that might mean,

00:45:38.522 --> 00:45:40.480
and that's why hugging
Amma could be effective,

00:45:40.480 --> 00:45:41.470
because of that.

00:45:41.470 --> 00:45:42.850
But then the other side
is kind of like, well

00:45:42.850 --> 00:45:43.690
what's the feeling?

00:45:43.690 --> 00:45:45.010
Like she smelled really nice.

00:45:45.010 --> 00:45:47.290
Like it was a little sweaty, a
little uncomfortable, but like

00:45:47.290 --> 00:45:48.070
it was also nice.

00:45:48.070 --> 00:45:50.680
And that juxtaposition,
I mean, it was constant.

00:45:50.680 --> 00:45:53.250
Like there was a constant
dialogue in my head.

00:45:53.250 --> 00:45:57.640
It continues to be just the way
I work and navigate the world,

00:45:57.640 --> 00:45:59.740
but that was very,
very hard for me

00:45:59.740 --> 00:46:01.840
and I would keep
flipping back and forth.

00:46:01.840 --> 00:46:04.330
And I do address it
a lot in the book

00:46:04.330 --> 00:46:07.735
because I think so many of us
are in the same position where

00:46:07.735 --> 00:46:10.060
it's like we're raised to
think a very specific way,

00:46:10.060 --> 00:46:11.890
and we're educated
and overeducated

00:46:11.890 --> 00:46:13.540
and sort of repeating
things again

00:46:13.540 --> 00:46:16.339
and again to become
experts at something.

00:46:16.339 --> 00:46:18.130
And then here's this
whole set of questions

00:46:18.130 --> 00:46:19.650
that are truly not Googleable.

00:46:19.650 --> 00:46:21.790
You will not find a
satisfactory answer.

00:46:21.790 --> 00:46:24.580
You will find people purporting
to know the answers on Google

00:46:24.580 --> 00:46:26.140
to all these questions.

00:46:26.140 --> 00:46:28.240
I would challenge
that maybe there are

00:46:28.240 --> 00:46:29.500
incorrect answers on Google.

00:46:29.500 --> 00:46:31.630
You need to tweak the algorithm
on these particular things,

00:46:31.630 --> 00:46:33.650
but there are just things
that are unknowable.

00:46:33.650 --> 00:46:37.260
And so if you start--

00:46:37.260 --> 00:46:39.160
I don't know how you
reconcile those things,

00:46:39.160 --> 00:46:40.540
but I kind of flip
back and forth too.

00:46:40.540 --> 00:46:41.890
But then ultimately,
it was like,

00:46:41.890 --> 00:46:43.348
I've just got to
suspend disbelief.

00:46:43.348 --> 00:46:47.260
Like I can't try to
explain these things,

00:46:47.260 --> 00:46:49.850
otherwise, I'll just
be stuck in a loop.

00:46:49.850 --> 00:46:51.680
AUDIENCE: Just as
a small follow-up,

00:46:51.680 --> 00:46:53.680
when you were actually
having these experiences,

00:46:53.680 --> 00:46:56.760
did you just like push aside any
of the thoughts that are like,

00:46:56.760 --> 00:46:58.042
OK, why is this happening?

00:46:58.042 --> 00:46:58.750
ANJALI KUMAR: No.

00:46:58.750 --> 00:47:00.430
I think I did it
really unsuccessfully.

00:47:00.430 --> 00:47:03.060
There were moments that I would,
like the tantric sound healing

00:47:03.060 --> 00:47:04.060
being a perfect example.

00:47:04.060 --> 00:47:05.850
There are moments where I
was like, this is so weird.

00:47:05.850 --> 00:47:07.410
And like my head
was like, oh my god.

00:47:07.410 --> 00:47:08.260
I cannot believe--

00:47:08.260 --> 00:47:09.400
I should not be doing this.

00:47:09.400 --> 00:47:11.000
My parents, like what
would they think?

00:47:11.000 --> 00:47:12.510
Like they're going
to hear about this.

00:47:12.510 --> 00:47:13.130
I'm going to write.

00:47:13.130 --> 00:47:14.530
I can't write about-- like
I was going on and on.

00:47:14.530 --> 00:47:15.520
I was like, this is bananas.

00:47:15.520 --> 00:47:16.180
I am married.

00:47:16.180 --> 00:47:17.070
Like what am I doing?

00:47:17.070 --> 00:47:19.090
You know, it was just like
a loop, a loop, a loop.

00:47:19.090 --> 00:47:20.330
And then there are moments
where I was kind of like,

00:47:20.330 --> 00:47:21.250
all right, just like relax.

00:47:21.250 --> 00:47:23.140
Just breathe into it,
and I was like, oh.

00:47:23.140 --> 00:47:25.720
It's kind of nice.

00:47:25.720 --> 00:47:28.660
Like this is bizarre,
but also kind

00:47:28.660 --> 00:47:30.560
of not altogether unpleasant.

00:47:30.560 --> 00:47:31.894
And then I'd be like, oh my god.

00:47:31.894 --> 00:47:33.851
I can't believe this man
is lying on top of me.

00:47:33.851 --> 00:47:34.770
This is very awkward.

00:47:34.770 --> 00:47:36.880
And so it would just be
like a constant thing.

00:47:36.880 --> 00:47:39.160
And that, for me, is
also my meditation cycle,

00:47:39.160 --> 00:47:42.474
is like the monkey mind of the
loop of like, what's going on?

00:47:42.474 --> 00:47:43.390
I have to make dinner.

00:47:43.390 --> 00:47:44.170
I have to go do this thing.

00:47:44.170 --> 00:47:45.340
I forgot to pick up
the dry cleaning.

00:47:45.340 --> 00:47:45.730
Blah, blah, blah.

00:47:45.730 --> 00:47:46.260
And then I'm like, oh.

00:47:46.260 --> 00:47:46.890
I'm suppose to be meditating.

00:47:46.890 --> 00:47:48.100
I'm like, mantra,
mantra, mantra, mantra.

00:47:48.100 --> 00:47:48.890
I'm like ah.

00:47:48.890 --> 00:47:50.510
And I'm like, crap,
so I fall asleep.

00:47:50.510 --> 00:47:53.270
And I just keep going
and it's like constant.

00:47:53.270 --> 00:47:56.146
And I feel like that's
the very human journey.

00:47:56.146 --> 00:47:57.520
I don't live in
the woods, right?

00:47:57.520 --> 00:47:59.890
Like I don't live on
a meditation farm.

00:47:59.890 --> 00:48:01.000
I live in New York City.

00:48:01.000 --> 00:48:01.900
I live downtown.

00:48:01.900 --> 00:48:02.800
I take the subway.

00:48:02.800 --> 00:48:03.550
I walk everywhere.

00:48:03.550 --> 00:48:06.680
Like it is hectic and I think
that's just part of our life,

00:48:06.680 --> 00:48:09.814
but if you can push that reset
button every day in some way.

00:48:09.814 --> 00:48:12.230
And the fact that you're just
asking the questions I think

00:48:12.230 --> 00:48:13.649
is great.

00:48:13.649 --> 00:48:14.690
AUDIENCE: Well thank you.

00:48:14.690 --> 00:48:15.752
Appreciate it.

00:48:15.752 --> 00:48:17.500
ANJALI KUMAR: Going
back this way.

00:48:17.500 --> 00:48:18.530
AUDIENCE: Hi.

00:48:18.530 --> 00:48:19.290
Nice to see you.

00:48:19.290 --> 00:48:21.380
Thank you for coming in.

00:48:21.380 --> 00:48:22.850
How did you know--

00:48:22.850 --> 00:48:24.350
it sounds like
you got to a point

00:48:24.350 --> 00:48:27.830
where you felt at peace,
that you had searched enough.

00:48:27.830 --> 00:48:30.904
You didn't find specific answers
and you were OK with that.

00:48:30.904 --> 00:48:31.820
Can you describe that?

00:48:31.820 --> 00:48:34.153
Because when you're just
talking about the constant loop

00:48:34.153 --> 00:48:36.530
and it's really hard
to break that cycle,

00:48:36.530 --> 00:48:39.060
how did you feel
fulfilled on this journey

00:48:39.060 --> 00:48:40.880
and what was that
moment like for you?

00:48:40.880 --> 00:48:41.930
ANJALI KUMAR:
There were a couple

00:48:41.930 --> 00:48:43.040
of things that drove that.

00:48:43.040 --> 00:48:45.470
I think one was definitely
the silent meditation

00:48:45.470 --> 00:48:48.050
experience of just being
still for that long.

00:48:48.050 --> 00:48:49.400
I didn't do a full 10 days.

00:48:49.400 --> 00:48:51.440
I tell that story
of why in the book,

00:48:51.440 --> 00:48:54.410
but I did a five-day retreat.

00:48:54.410 --> 00:48:58.300
And by the end, I was like, I
think I'm good for a minute.

00:48:58.300 --> 00:49:00.156
Like I feel like just
stopping and I just

00:49:00.156 --> 00:49:02.030
need to sit with what
I've already researched

00:49:02.030 --> 00:49:05.870
and sort of be in that, and
feel like I have enough data

00:49:05.870 --> 00:49:09.920
to inform something
that felt right.

00:49:09.920 --> 00:49:11.712
And then also, truthfully,
it was partially

00:49:11.712 --> 00:49:12.794
because I was on deadline.

00:49:12.794 --> 00:49:14.240
I was like, I can't
keep searching

00:49:14.240 --> 00:49:15.910
and I've got to
turn this book in,

00:49:15.910 --> 00:49:20.510
and I have to be OK with
not having a conclusion

00:49:20.510 --> 00:49:23.520
because I'm not going to in
time for this book to come out.

00:49:23.520 --> 00:49:25.400
And so either I can
spend the rest of my life

00:49:25.400 --> 00:49:29.210
writing this book and it'll
be written and published

00:49:29.210 --> 00:49:32.630
posthumously, or I can
try to wrap this up and be

00:49:32.630 --> 00:49:34.790
OK with the knowledge
that I will never know

00:49:34.790 --> 00:49:36.200
the answer to these questions.

00:49:36.200 --> 00:49:38.450
And that's where
I chose to land.

00:49:38.450 --> 00:49:39.220
AUDIENCE: Sorry.

00:49:39.220 --> 00:49:39.720
Thank you.

00:49:39.720 --> 00:49:42.440
One more question.

00:49:42.440 --> 00:49:44.300
It sounds like the
impetus of this search

00:49:44.300 --> 00:49:46.470
was more about your
daughter and the questions

00:49:46.470 --> 00:49:48.410
she might have as
she grows older.

00:49:48.410 --> 00:49:51.297
When did you decide,
hey, this is a book,

00:49:51.297 --> 00:49:53.630
and I should probably put
this out there for more people

00:49:53.630 --> 00:49:54.650
to absorb?

00:49:54.650 --> 00:49:55.430
ANJALI KUMAR: Ooh.

00:49:55.430 --> 00:49:56.440
That's a good question.

00:49:56.440 --> 00:49:58.615
There was a moment where
it was going to be a film,

00:49:58.615 --> 00:50:00.740
and then I realized I did
not want to be in a film,

00:50:00.740 --> 00:50:04.592
and so that was pushed aside.

00:50:04.592 --> 00:50:06.050
But I felt like
there was something

00:50:06.050 --> 00:50:08.570
I wanted to do with it because
it was fun and anyone I would

00:50:08.570 --> 00:50:11.930
tell the stories to would be
like, you have to write this

00:50:11.930 --> 00:50:12.430
down.

00:50:12.430 --> 00:50:14.055
These are such funny
stories or they're

00:50:14.055 --> 00:50:17.450
really interesting or whatever,
depending on what story it was.

00:50:17.450 --> 00:50:20.390
So I started taking better
notes as I would do things.

00:50:20.390 --> 00:50:23.270
And then I met an
agent a few years ago,

00:50:23.270 --> 00:50:25.020
and he was like, you've
got to write this.

00:50:25.020 --> 00:50:27.222
Like, this is a book
I know I can sell it.

00:50:27.222 --> 00:50:28.680
And that's what
ended up happening.

00:50:28.680 --> 00:50:30.950
So I never set out
to write a book.

00:50:30.950 --> 00:50:32.349
It just sort of--

00:50:32.349 --> 00:50:34.390
and it sounds like such
a jerky thing to be like,

00:50:34.390 --> 00:50:36.848
it just sort of happened, but
that's kind of what happened.

00:50:36.848 --> 00:50:38.920
It felt like, you know,
Jesus took the wheel.

00:50:38.920 --> 00:50:40.430
No, I'm just joking.

00:50:40.430 --> 00:50:44.330
That's inappropriate, but I just
feel like it just sort of just

00:50:44.330 --> 00:50:46.960
played out the way it
was meant to I think.

00:50:46.960 --> 00:50:48.804
Yeah.

00:50:48.804 --> 00:50:49.970
AUDIENCE: I have a question.

00:50:49.970 --> 00:50:53.024
How forthcoming were you when
you went and traveled around

00:50:53.024 --> 00:50:54.440
and met with
different-- like when

00:50:54.440 --> 00:50:55.731
you went to the Wiccan potluck.

00:50:55.731 --> 00:50:57.300
Did they ask you
why you were there?

00:50:57.300 --> 00:50:58.050
Did you tell them?

00:50:58.050 --> 00:50:59.589
And if so, what
was the response?

00:50:59.589 --> 00:51:00.380
ANJALI KUMAR: Yeah.

00:51:00.380 --> 00:51:02.170
I was incredibly forthcoming.

00:51:02.170 --> 00:51:03.200
I am a lawyer.

00:51:03.200 --> 00:51:05.120
I do not want to
get sued by anybody.

00:51:05.120 --> 00:51:06.860
I wasn't trying to dupe anybody.

00:51:06.860 --> 00:51:09.680
I was very, very clear that--

00:51:09.680 --> 00:51:11.750
once I decided to
turn it into a book,

00:51:11.750 --> 00:51:13.700
I was very clear that
I was writing a book.

00:51:13.700 --> 00:51:17.150
And for anybody that
was prior chapters,

00:51:17.150 --> 00:51:18.650
I reached out to
people to make sure

00:51:18.650 --> 00:51:19.970
that they were OK with
what I was writing,

00:51:19.970 --> 00:51:21.720
because everything
in the book was true.

00:51:21.720 --> 00:51:24.410
And so any one that,
certainly if I named them,

00:51:24.410 --> 00:51:26.660
I gave everyone the opportunity
to change their name

00:51:26.660 --> 00:51:29.510
or to read what I was writing
because I didn't want anyone

00:51:29.510 --> 00:51:34.970
to feel made fun of
or kind of sideswiped

00:51:34.970 --> 00:51:36.830
from what I was writing,
because it was not

00:51:36.830 --> 00:51:40.640
meant to be like a take down of
all these different practices,

00:51:40.640 --> 00:51:43.725
so I was very, very
forthcoming when I did it.

00:51:43.725 --> 00:51:45.850
Thank you from the legal
team of Google for asking.

00:51:48.736 --> 00:51:50.780
AUDIENCE: Were there
any ways in which

00:51:50.780 --> 00:51:52.700
you feel like your
life has been changed

00:51:52.700 --> 00:51:54.560
in either positive
or negative ways

00:51:54.560 --> 00:51:56.936
that you were not expecting
after this experience?

00:51:56.936 --> 00:51:58.560
ANJALI KUMAR: From
the research or just

00:51:58.560 --> 00:51:59.580
from the whole experience?

00:51:59.580 --> 00:52:00.490
AUDIENCE: The research,
writing, anything.

00:52:00.490 --> 00:52:01.100
Yeah.

00:52:01.100 --> 00:52:01.940
ANJALI KUMAR: Yeah.

00:52:01.940 --> 00:52:03.523
It's opened up in
ways that I wouldn't

00:52:03.523 --> 00:52:04.790
have expected for sure.

00:52:04.790 --> 00:52:07.490
I think just what it did was--

00:52:07.490 --> 00:52:08.310
one of the habits.

00:52:08.310 --> 00:52:10.490
I think I learned
working at Google

00:52:10.490 --> 00:52:12.870
actually was to be
ready for anything

00:52:12.870 --> 00:52:16.015
and to really put myself into
uncomfortable situations.

00:52:16.015 --> 00:52:18.500
Like again, as a lawyer, you're
trained to know something,

00:52:18.500 --> 00:52:21.140
to go really deep on that
issue, to really be the expert.

00:52:21.140 --> 00:52:23.566
And working at Google
in the years that I did,

00:52:23.566 --> 00:52:25.190
that was not going
to be the situation.

00:52:25.190 --> 00:52:26.480
It was like, here's
a new product.

00:52:26.480 --> 00:52:27.590
We're launching
this other thing,

00:52:27.590 --> 00:52:29.330
and you just had to
go figure it out.

00:52:29.330 --> 00:52:32.300
And working that
muscle here I think

00:52:32.300 --> 00:52:34.250
led to me being
really comfortable

00:52:34.250 --> 00:52:36.770
going into these very
uncomfortable situations

00:52:36.770 --> 00:52:38.900
for the research for
this book, and has

00:52:38.900 --> 00:52:42.050
become a theme of both my
career and my personal life

00:52:42.050 --> 00:52:44.316
since then, where it's
been like it's just

00:52:44.316 --> 00:52:45.440
opened up all these things.

00:52:45.440 --> 00:52:47.846
Because something like
becoming a clown in the Macy's

00:52:47.846 --> 00:52:49.970
Thanksgiving Day Parade,
like that is not something

00:52:49.970 --> 00:52:51.950
I would ever have
thought I would do.

00:52:51.950 --> 00:52:54.900
And I went and I had so
much fun and it was so goofy

00:52:54.900 --> 00:52:57.440
and it was such a
delightful thing to do,

00:52:57.440 --> 00:53:00.605
and I think it's because
I worked at Google

00:53:00.605 --> 00:53:03.230
and then did something like this
that I'm willing to put myself

00:53:03.230 --> 00:53:05.965
out there and sort of suck
the marrow out of life

00:53:05.965 --> 00:53:06.834
while I'm here.

00:53:06.834 --> 00:53:08.250
And I think that's
definitely what

00:53:08.250 --> 00:53:09.660
this has taught me, for sure.

00:53:12.754 --> 00:53:15.060
CRISTIN FRODELLA: Thank
you, Anjali, for coming.

00:53:15.060 --> 00:53:16.750
And I think if we've
learned anything,

00:53:16.750 --> 00:53:19.882
it's that in addition to
wanting love and health

00:53:19.882 --> 00:53:20.840
and what was the other?

00:53:20.840 --> 00:53:21.330
ANJALI KUMAR: Happiness.

00:53:21.330 --> 00:53:22.663
CRISTIN FRODELLA: And happiness.

00:53:22.663 --> 00:53:24.690
I think also,
everybody kind of wants

00:53:24.690 --> 00:53:26.800
to know what's it all about.

00:53:26.800 --> 00:53:30.850
So thanks for bringing us
together to talk about that.

00:53:30.850 --> 00:53:35.820
And if you haven't read the
book yet, I highly recommend it.

00:53:35.820 --> 00:53:36.660
It's so much fun.

00:53:36.660 --> 00:53:37.980
It's such a fun journey.

00:53:37.980 --> 00:53:40.350
At the back of the
room, pick up a copy.

00:53:40.350 --> 00:53:41.819
And it's nice to see you all.

00:53:41.819 --> 00:53:43.610
ANJALI KUMAR: Thank
you all for being here.

